04804nam a22005655i 9780773565135DE-B159720230529101353.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||230529t19941994xxc    fo  d z      eng d  a97807735651357 a10.1515/97807735651352doi  a(DE-B1597)654939  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  axxccCA 4aD768.15bV354 1994eb 7aHIS0271302bisacsh04a791.45/721 aBercuson, David J., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aValour and the Horror Revisited /cWise, David J. Bercuson. 1aMontreal ;aKingston ;aLondon ;aChicago : bMcGill-Queen's University Press, c[1994] 4c©1994  a1 online resource (192 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFront Matter -- tContents -- tDrama or Documentary? -- tIntroduction -- tThe Valour and the Horror: A Report for the CBC Ombudsman -- tThe Valour and the Horror: A Historical Analysis -- tThe Ombudsman Controversy -- tReport of the CBC Ombudsman -- tResponse to the CBC Ombudsman Report, November 10,1992, Galafilm Inc. -- tLetter to the Globe and Mail and the Montreal Gazette -- tComments on the November 10 Galafilm Report, 18 November 1992 -- tHistorians' Commentary -- tSavage Christmas: The Canadians at Hong Kong -- tThe Canadians on Verrieres Ridge: A Historiographical Survey -- tIn the Shadow of Death by Moonlight -- tThe Valour and the Horror Controversy and the Official History of the Royal Canadian Air Force, Volume 3 -- tContributors0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIn January 1992 the Canadian Broadcasting Corporation (CBC) broadcast The Valour and the Horror, a three-part television series on Canada's role in World War II. It sparked a major controversy among viewers, war veterans, and historians. Brian and Terence McKenna, the authors-producers of the series, were accused of distorting historical facts, maligning individuals such as commanders Arthur Harris and Guy Simonds, presenting a biased account of events, and overstepping the line between journalism and drama. The Valour and the Horror Revisited brings together source documents, original essays, and commentaries to provide an analysis of the specific accusations and of larger questions concerning responsible journalism. Included in the collection are reports by David Bercuson and S.F. Wise, who were asked by the CBC ombudsman to assess the series; the CBC ombudsman's report; the McKennas' response to the ombudsman's report; the ombudsman's commentary on the McKennas' response; and three new essays by historians John Ferris, William McAndrew, and Scot Robertson on the incidents covered in the series - Canadian involvement in the battles in Hong Kong and Normandy, and the bombing of Germany. The Valour and the Horror Revisited addresses such important issues as the dangers of "docudrama," the calibre of the Canadian media, the meaning of the Canadian experience in the war, and the nature of history.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 7aHISTORY / Military / Wars & Conflicts (Other).2bisacsh1 aBercuson, David J., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBrian,, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFerris, John, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMcandrew, Bill, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMckenna, Terence, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMorgan, William, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aRobertson, Scot, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aWise, , eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut1 aWise, S.F, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aWise, S.F., e